        <section class="article-information-group toggle-content is-visible" id="article-information">

			
							<section class="article-information abstract">
					<h2>Abstract</h2>
					The evidence for the United States points to balanced growth despite falling investment good prices and a less-than-unitary elasticity of substitution between capital and labor. This is inconsistent with the Uzawa Growth Theorem. We extend Uzawa's theorem to show that the introduction of human capital accumulation in the standard way does not resolve the puzzle. However, balanced growth is possible if education is endogenous and capital is more complementary with schooling than with raw labor. We present a class of aggregate production functions for which a neoclassical growth model with capital-augmenting technological progress and endogenous schooling converges to a balanced growth path.				</section>
			
							<section class="article-information citation">
					<h2>Citation</h2>
					<cite>

                        Grossman, Gene M., Elhanan Helpman, Ezra Oberfield, and Thomas Sampson.
						<span class="year">2017.</span>

						
						
							<span class="title">"Balanced Growth Despite Uzawa."</span>
						
						<span class="journal">American Economic Review</span>,

							  <span class="vol">
					107 (4):
					 1293-1312<span
									  class="pages">.</span>
				  </span>
						<span class="doi">DOI: 10.1257/aer.20151739</span>
					</cite>

